column12: I agree that in theory, iNat can be used to study feral populations, but I also think that systematically marking escapees or non-captives as wild actually prevents studying feral population with iNat data. If we look at the map for wild Budgerigars https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?captive=false&place_id=any&subview=map&taxon_id=19339, they are found all across USA and Europe. Now, a lot of those are actually captives that haven't been properly marked as such, but a lot of them are also escapees marked as wild (and where there is a lot of disagreements on this between observers/identifiers it seems). How can we determine where there are feral or invasive populations of Budgerigars with this map? Unless I am mistaken, I don't think that there are feral populations all across Europe or
